  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 965994f2c96676e4cb5c993fc6354aab, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  paintingTitle: The Hay Wain
  artistName: John Constable
  paintingDescription: "The view is of the millpond at Flatford on the River Stour.
    Flatford Mill was a watermill for grinding corn, operated by the Constable family
    for nearly a hundred years. It still survives and is about a mile from Constable\u2019s
    birthplace at East Bergholt, Suffolk. The house on the left also survives; in
    Constable\u2019s time it was occupied by tenant farmer Willy Lott.\r\n\r\nThe
    title, The Hay Wain, refers to the wooden wagon (wain) used for transporting
    cut and dried meadow grass (hay). The empty wagon is making its way through the
    shallow water to cross to the meadow on the other side where haymakers are at
    work.\r\n\r\nAlthough the painting evokes a Suffolk scene, it was created in
    the artist\u2019s studio in London. Working from a number of open-air sketches
    made over several years, Constable then made a full-size preparatory oil sketch
    to establish the composition before painting the final picture."
  paintingImage: {fileID: 2800000, guid: 7cc925ffe101f8b478f7a10c158694ca, type: 3}
  orientation: 0
  frameThickness: 0.15
  artworkDepth: 0.04
  frameDepth: 0.12
  artworkMesh: {fileID: 4268899396775418999}
  frameTop: {fileID: 7726194831652057595}
  frameBottom: {fileID: 3982804440131098909}
  frameLeft: {fileID: 6716207485038074755}
  frameRight: {fileID: 7829242131297469281}
